{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538660","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538660"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:30:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:30:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16259"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16259","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16259"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.56,0.06,0.12,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8950"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64543"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8950","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8950"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16259"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49976"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"297"},{"type":"tags","id":"2718"},{"type":"tags","id":"4176"},{"type":"tags","id":"4210"},{"type":"tags","id":"4382"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21292"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39876"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43625"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64543","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64543"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 22-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of light vaginal bleeding after intercourse. She also reports occasional spotting between periods. She has been using the combined oral contraceptive pill for four years. She has no significant medical history and takes no other regular medications. She has never had cervical screening due to her age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Speculum examination reveals a healthy-looking cervix with a red, velvety area around the external os that bleeds slightly when touched.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cervical screening test","Cervical co-test","Cryotherapy of the cervix","Immediate colposcopy referral","Cessation of oral contraceptive pill"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with postcoital bleeding and intermenstrual bleeding, with examination findings consistent with cervical ectropion. This is a common, benign condition where columnar epithelium extends onto the ectocervix, creating a red, velvety appearance that bleeds easily on contact. It is particularly common in young women and those using hormonal contraception.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECervical co-test\u003C/strong\u003E (both HPV and liquid-based cytology) is the most appropriate first step when a patient presents with symptoms such as postcoital bleeding, regardless of age. While routine cervical screening in Australia typically begins at age 25, earlier testing is warranted when there are symptoms that could indicate cervical pathology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECervical screening test\u003C/strong\u003E alone (HPV test) would be appropriate for asymptomatic screening but is insufficient when symptoms are present, as cytology is also required to assess for cellular changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate colposcopy referral\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if there were suspicious cervical lesions or an abnormal screening test, but is not necessary for typical cervical ectropion findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECryotherapy of the cervix\u003C/strong\u003E is sometimes used to treat symptomatic cervical ectropion, but would only be considered after cervical pathology has been excluded and if symptoms are significantly bothersome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECessation of oral contraceptive pill\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary as cervical ectropion, while more common in women using hormonal contraception, is a benign finding that does not require treatment unless symptomatic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile cervical ectropion is a benign condition that often requires no treatment, it is important to exclude other causes of postcoital bleeding through appropriate screening. If symptoms are bothersome after normal screening results, various treatment options can be discussed including cautery or cryotherapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cervical ectropion is a common, benign finding where columnar epithelium extends onto the ectocervix.","Postcoital bleeding and intermenstrual bleeding warrant cervical co-testing regardless of age.","Cervical ectropion does not increase the risk of cervical cancer and does not require treatment unless symptomatic."],"references":["Aggarwal P, Ben Amor A. Cervical ectropion [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 [cited 2024 Nov 23]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK560709/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49976"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16259"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49976","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49976"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-23T19:45:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-23T19:46:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8950"}},"content":{"data":{"typ